Glad I was watching holy hell.

&amp;#x200B;

AAPL took a giant shit too, chart is hilarious.

Rationale: Broadcom is currently worth over $800 on a DCF basis, and more like over ~$1200 if it were stretched on the valuation/in line with other stocks.  I know that puts the price off the charts technically and is laughably high, but it is what it is.  I have no idea why its trading where it is.  Usually there is an issue with the stock but its really a straightforward business with a large moat and is universally recommended by analysis's on the street.  The cash flow growth is 11% on average and the dividend yield is almost 5% right now.  Its trading at historically low RSI levels on the monthly (this is where it was before it rocketed 300% the last time around).  

&amp;nbsp;

With that said, this is my set up.  A 2 year time horizon to see this rocket and a short term put hedge to get us through this virus situation (no idea if further impact will be worth the option but just like to limit volatility on uncertain events).  Taking a chance here and hoping it pays off down the line.

\&gt;In the B2B sector these contracts are all annualized. Businesses won't  cancel salesforce and square unless they're literally failing, which  is/will happen, but probably not enough to impact short term  valuations....yet...

&amp;#x200B;

Worked in ecommerce software for 4+ years. Beyond being annualized contracts (and, in fact, usually 3 year contracts on auto-renewal) the kinds of implementations that use these tech's are generally boutique hand-built custom things. That's the entire point of Square's API in many ways. Most of the companies which use these tech's are the kinds that do major tech upgrades/replatforming every 10-20 years or so. People who bought into Salesforce in 2008 are probably in the market for smth new, but people who bought into Square will probably stay with their current implementations until at least 2030.

One doesn't work, has terrible execution, no support of any sort, will literally rob you of the money. 

&amp;#x200B;

The other one if Fidelity.
